posts.body:
It is in the process of becoming cucked to hell and back by glowniggers. I am attaching the PDF of Jimbo's testimony so you can read through it yourself, but here are the highlights:
>Received increased law enforcement requests after Christchurch, from 1-2 a month to over 100

The time for centralized imageboards is over. 4chan died from internal censorship, 8chan died from glownigger infiltration. This has and will continue to happen for all other clearnet, centralized imageboards. Someone will be held accountable and the site will either be shut down or cucked to the point of being entirely unusable. If you return to 8chan, expect your IP to be immediately logged and archived by glowniggers if it isn't already. 
Web 3.0 is our best option, with ZeroNet being the best we have right now. We are fully capable of monitoring ourselves. We have transcended being governed over by authorities that fuck us over at every turn, it's only us now. However, as you should all be aware, while ZeroNet is theoretically impossible to shut down, it's less secure than a clearnet site as raw IPs are visible to all users, and the antispam measure that Acid implemented through ZeroID basically means everyone is forced to use a username (whether this is temporary or not I'm not sure, we should offer other solutions ASAP). Remember to always use proper OPSEC and only run ZeroNet while behind TOR or a good VPN, and encrypt the install folder using VeraCrypt or TrueCrypt if you're really worried.
Welcome to the next generation. Stay safe brothers.

posts.subject: Frogs have the right to resell Steam games
posts.body:
>A court in France has ruled that Steam users have the right to resell their games, following a case brought against the digital storefront giant by consumer group UFC Que Choisir in 2015.

>The consumer group initially bought the case to the District Court of Paris (as reported by French websites Next Impact and Numerama) in order to contest the legality of certain clauses within Steam's Subscriber Agreement under European law. Of primary concern was UFC Que Choisir's belief that digital games should, like their physical counterparts, be eligible for resale.

>Ultimately, judges agreed with the organisation, using a 2012 European Court ruling (which said that a transaction for digital goods still implies the transfer of the right of ownership) as the basis of its decision, saying that Valve "can no longer oppose the resale of this copy...even if the initial purchase is made by downloading". Valve's terms attempted to frame a sale as a 'subscription' to a product, but the court ruled that users were, in fact, purchasing licenses, enabling European law to come into play.

>A number of other rulings we made in favour of the UFC Que Choisir too, with the court proclaiming that fourteen clauses in Valve's Steam Subscriber Agreement could not be enforced. For instance, judges said Valve cannot legally keep the contents of Steam Wallet funds when a user leaves the platform, and users should be reimbursed when requested. Additionally, it said that Valve should accept responsibility when software used on its platform harms a user, even if it's in beta, should reduce its claim on mods and user-created content, and must be clearer about the ways players can lose access to their Steam library for poor conduct.

>If Valve refuses to abide by the ruling and post the French court's decision to Steam within a month, it will have to pay a fine of 3,000 Euros per day for up to six months.

>With this success in the bag, the UFC Que Choisir says it plans to take action against other platforms and products - although it's worth noting that the case isn't yet closed. Valve still has the right to appeal and, as Doug Lombardi told PC Gamer in a statement following the ruling, that's exactly what the company plans to do.

>"We disagree with the decision of the Paris Court of First Instance and will appeal it," said Lombardi, "The decision will have no effect on Steam while the case is on appeal".

>This isn't the first time that Valve has been involved with courts over its perceived anti-consumer practices, of course. In 2014, the Australian Competition and Consumer Commission sued Valve (ultimately with success) over its failure to comply with local consumer law by denying purchasers the right to refund their games. The ACCC argued that while Valve had no physical presence in the country, the goods it sold were still subject to local law.

https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2019-09-19-french-court-rules-steam-users-have-right-to-resell-their-games

The first Halo I played was when my sister got Halo 2 for Christmas in 2006. I knew what Halo was but never got a chance to play it because I was a young bab and didn't have the money/knowledge to get good games. I'm not super autistic about the overall lore and storyline, but I know enough to understand what makes a good game and what doesn't.

>Halo: Combat Evolved
Never actually played it until a few years ago, I picked it up at a flea market a couple years ago for $3. While it may have been the "holy fuck this is amazing" killer app almost two decades ago, it's aged like milk. Environments are very blurry/samey (I spent half an hour backtracking by accident because everything looked the same), levels are repetitive and tedious (library comes to mind), vehicles control like the tires are made of ice driving on ice. But for what it was and given the context of its time, it's still a good enough game. Also the most straightforward plotwise since they didn't know if it was going to hit or bomb so they kept it simple.

>Halo 2
Easily the best in the whole series. Story is a logical continuation of the first one and also expanded the lore but it all stays in the game and doesn't rely on outside comics/books like a lot of games today. Found the key to good gameplay/gunplay and haven't really changed it since. Environments are distinctive and diverse, grafics still hold up good today, hard rock soundtrack is god tier. Just wish they weren't working on 24/7 crunch time and gave a less cliffhanger ending. Multiplayer was also real good but it was past my time, the few LAN games I played were really fun though.

>Halo 3
Didn't get to play it until about five years after it came about because poorfag, so I spent those five years tediously playing through Halo 2 over and over again (somehow never got one skull though, lmao). Story felt underwhelming compared to 2, so much buildup and it kind of fizzles out towards the end. Gameplay is mostly unchanged, a few new gunz that are either hit or miss in terms of how they feel/damage. Environments are a lot brighter than 2, probably because they wanted to show off what they could do with the new xbawks. Soundtrack feels like a major step down from 2, it's hard to go from hard rock to orchestral. I remember the multiplayer being incredibly frustrating and tedious, but again, beyond my time. Everytime I got back to play through the campaign thinking "maybe it's better than I remember" I just keep feeling underwhelmed. It has its moments, but nothing on the scale of 2.

>Halo Reach
Dad gave it to me while parents went on vacation for a week, beat it completely in that time. Don't have many memories from it except dying a lot. Story kind of takes a backseat and plays out naturally, you get the feeling that you're fighting a losing war towards the end. New (old) gunz have a heavier feel to them, but gameplay is still the same. Armor abilities aren't much more than a gimmick, I'd forget I even had them. Space shootan' level was too short, thought it'd be something recurring throughout the game. Looks a whole lot better than 3. Don't remember any of the music. Never even touched the multiplayer. People are really divided on this one, I don't have any strong opinions one way or the other.

>Halo 3: ODST
The last one in the series I played. Very atmospheric in the beginning, going around at night and finding what happened to the others. Very similar to Reach in gameplay/graphics (but 720p max resolution what the fuck). Anons seem to consider it the best in the whole series, which makes me think I missed something the first time I went through it. 360 is at my parents' place though so that'll have to wait.

>Halo 4 **unpopular opinion incoming**
The first game in the series I played when it was actually still relevant. The story isn't as bad as people say it is, I like how it focused on the relationship between Cheef and Cortana. Forerunner part was good too **Bungie kind of set up for it at the end of 3**. Story did make a few key decisions I don't agree with, killing Cortana and such. Gameplay is very tight, sounds are crispy, new gunz are very fun to use. Easily the best looking game on the 360 and the environments are some of the best in the series and in really the whole sci-fi genre, it really feels like you're on a hostile alien world. Don't remember much from the soundtrack. Multiplayer was some of the most fun I had online in 2012-2013, lot of good memories. Spartan Ops is a joke, literally just "go here push this button go back" on the same five maps twenty different times. People are always hating on this one, but aside from Spartan Ops I don't understand why.

>Halo 5
No opinion whatsoever. Considered the worst by far, but I haven't ever played it or know anything about it. Probably just going to watch a full playthrough on JewTube someday because I'm not buying an Xbone to play one game.

>Halo Wars
No opinion, haven't played. Never been a fan of the RTS genre anyways.

>5000/5000 character limit
